The paper proposes a method for automated detection of motion-related artefacts in cardiac magnetic resonance (CMR) images using 3D spatio-temporal Convolutional Neural Networks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The use of deep learning techniques also suggests that the paper may belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper deals with medical images, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a novel data augmentation approach, which suggests that it may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
